{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2ffd6250-4d83-442c-89b0-91981ee86352","content":"The best approach is `dotnet-trace` with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already in the container)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app/).\n\n**Tips for K8s:**\n- `kubectl cp` the `.nettrace` file out of the pod afterward.\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a sidecar or ephemeral debug container:\n  ```bash\n  kubectl debug -it <pod> --image=mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/monitor/base:8 --target=<container>\n  ```\n- For lower overhead or longer collection, consider `dotnet-counters` first to confirm it's truly CPU-bound, then trace.\n\n**Alternative — `perf` (native + managed):**\n```bash\nperf record -g -p <PID> -- sleep 30\n```\nRequires `perf` in the container and `SYS_ADMIN` / `perfmon` capabilities, which most K8s clusters restrict.\n\n`dotnet-trace` is usually the path of least resistance in a containerized environment.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1aa11666-b5f4-488d-be05-5942026d642a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question - I don't need to search a codebase or run commands. I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":422,"requestId":"5042:243E33:20BDF4:28DE2E:69F551D1"},"id":"258e2cc4-0e30-4337-9ed6-e970e0998dd1","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:22:36.488Z","parentId":"3b249630-eea9-4398-b0bd-0e3ef45df6f8"}
